@ctubbsii I was thinking it was an easy fix but wanted input from you and @keith-turner.  Can't we just have the master delete the zookeeper lock at https://github.com/apache/accumulo/blob/master/server/master/src/main/java/org/apache/accumulo/master/Master.java#L1230 ?

A tserver had hardware issues and got into a bad state.  It didn't go down, the master could not talk to it, but it didn't make progress on it's work for several days.  Because the master never reassigned those tablets, all query and ingest to those tablets hung. 

@jdwoody anything to add?

Solution for Hadoop DistributedCache an this web page works:  https://stackoverflow.com/a/26421057/196405

I modified the TokenFileIT test to make the these calls on the  hadoop.Job object in the run() method:

```java
  public int run(String[] args) throws Exception {
    ...
    job.addCacheFile(new URI("hdfs://localhost:8020/some_file.json#some"));
    job.addCacheFile(new URI("hdfs://localhost:8020/other_file.json#other"));
    ...
  }
```

I also added an override method for setup(context) in the integrated tests internal hadoop.mapper class like so:

```java
      protected void setup(Context context) throws IOException, InterruptedException {
        if (context.getCacheFiles() != null && context.getCacheFiles().length > 0) {

          File some_file = new File("./some");
          File other_file = new File("./other");

          BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("./some"));
          try {
            StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
            String line = br.readLine();

            while (line != null) {
              sb.append(line);
              sb.append(System.lineSeparator());
              line = br.readLine();
            }
            String everything = sb.toString();
          } finally {
            br.close();
          }

          // Do things to these two files, like read them
          // or parse as JSON or whatever.
        }
        super.setup(context);
      }
```

On my command line I added two small json files to HDFS via the commands:
 jzeiberg@dhcp-10-50-230-160  ~/.cache  hdfs dfs -put other_file.json / 
 jzeiberg@dhcp-10-50-230-160  ~/.cache  hdfs dfs -put some_file.json / 

When I ran the code in the debugger I was able to read the contents of the somefile.json in the setup function above using the "some" mnemonic specified by adding #some after the fully qualified hdfs URI in the job.addCacheFile function call.

Since this haddoop distributed cache works the way the stackoverflow webpage says it does I will now proceed to use this distributed cache method where we attempt to use distributed cache elsewhere in our code.
